(11. DMARC DNS record inheritance and DMARC alignment requirements) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-03-20T02:57:31Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/spam/DMARCAlignmentAndInheritance) Tj
T*
(To simplify, DMARC is based on the domain in the 'From:' header, and what policy \(if any\) that) Tj
T*
(domain specifies. As I've written about \(and rediscovered\) more than once \( here and here \),) Tj
T*
(DMARC will look up the DNS record for the DMARC policy in exactly one of two places, either in) Tj
T*
(the exact From: domain or on the organization's top level domain. In other words, if a message) Tj
T*
(has a From: of 'someone@breaking.news.example.org', a receiver will first look for a DMARC TXT) Tj
T*
(DNS record with the name _dmarc.breaking.news.example.org and then one with the name) Tj
T*
(_dmarc.example.org . \(But there will be no lookup for _dmarc.news.example.org .\) DMARC also has) Tj
T*
(the concept of policy inheritance , where the example.org DMARC DNS TXT record can specify a) Tj
T*
(different DMARC policy for the organizational domain than for subdomains that don't have their) Tj
T*
(own policy. For example, example.org could specify 'p=reject; sp=none' to say that 'From:) Tj
T*
(user@example.org' should be rejected if it fails DMARC but it has no views on a default for) Tj
ET
